Irene Chien & Videogame Culture
Irene Chien, Consortium for Faculty Diversity Fellow and visiting assistant professor of media & communication at Muhlenberg College, is quick to notice when her students begin playing a video game during class. Often, she’s the one who suggested the game in the first place.
Chien first introduced students to video games as a research subject through a special topics course last semester. Now, students in her media and society course are exploring games through perspectives grounded in the humanities, social sciences, engineering and technology. Her class explores the cultural impact and implications of videogame culture, particularly in a world that tends to think of “gamers” as a title reserved for young men.
She's particularly interested in the role of women in gaming as both creators and consumers of video games. Her students explored the media coverage surrounding "Gamergate," a recent national controversy involving gaming women who were harassed and threatened by online communities. Her students seek to understand how the event touched on historical and pervasive gender disparity in the culture of video games and associated “gamer” identities.
These difficult questions encourage the class to delve into how we think about games and how the videogame industry shapes the world around us.

“What is a game, and what is play?” Chien asks. “How has that shifted historically, from when people used to play with sticks, with just their bodies and outdoor space, to a game culture that includes computational devices that have become smaller and more portable.”
The class makes an early distinction between historical, analog concepts associated with games and the shift towards digital games. Her students study games as programs, as algorithms, as a series of processes. This research lens provides students with insight into how advancements in computing affect countless aspects of their lives.
She motions to an iPhone and points out that the small device is part of a ubiquitous industry of personal computers, many of which are equally capable of managing communication, finance and entertainment - including games. No longer are video games categorically inaccessible and representative of an elite, technologically adept subculture. Chien notes that the majority of American households now play video games, and more than half of game players are documented as women.
Chien’s students are rising to her challenges. A student recently approached her about forming a gaming club on campus. She advised the student that the term “gamer” is a term that comes with a heavily contested identity. The student quickly responded that, to him, a gamer was simply someone - anyone - who loves to play video games, regardless of skill level, game type or gender. Both agreed that such a specific statement was powerful, inclusive - a declaration that could be made even stronger when made a central tenet in the club’s bylaws.
And that’s exactly what her student did.


